The pattern of admission shows that the number of cases admitted to hospitals increased over the study period and that most cases of CAP occurred post Hajj (Figure 2
, Table 2
).

Hospital location and treatment in the ICU were significantly associated with S. pneumoniae CAP cases (p
 = 0.01). CAP patients admitted to Medina hospitals were less likely to have S. pneumoniae-attributable CAP than those admitted to Mecca hospitals (OR 0.33, 95% CI 0.14–0.80). CAP patients treated in the ICU were 2.88 times more likely to be S. pneumoniae CAP cases than those not treated in the ICU (OR 2.88, 95% CI 1.37–6.08). No significant association was observed between S. pneumoniae-attributable CAP and age, gender, pilgrim’s country of origin, antibiotic use in the 5 days prior to hospital admission, smoking, or diabetes status (Table 3
).
